that doesn't work. For some kids, it will work for a 
short period of time to threaten them. But in the

28:33.990 --> 28:36.053
long run, it doesn't work. The only way you can get 
students to do well in the academic courses is by

28:36.539 --> 28:57.679
setting up a specific educational plan to help 
them, to set up tutorial programs to give them that

28:36.539 --> 28:57.679
extra help they need, and to make the classroom 
experience exciting for them. When you do that,

28:57.699 --> 29:03.525
the key to doing that is to having high quality 
teachers. Instead of trying to use these

29:04.012 --> 29:13.363
mechanical mechanisms to threaten people, you 
really need creative teachers. You need smaller

29:13.383 --> 29:16.806
classes, better curriculum materials. You need 
the opportunity, the flexibility of the teacher

29:17.627 --> 29:30.542
to help students work at the level they're at and 
have them feel good about themselves and use

29:17.627 --> 29:30.542
success at the next level of their stage of 
intellectual development. and challenge them

29:31.349 --> 29:37.217
there instead of giving them some task that they 
can't do and they feel like a failure. The key to

29:37.877 --> 29:44.366
teaching is being able to differentiate 
instruction based on where that student is at the

29:37.877 --> 29:44.366
moment. And not to give them an assignment that's 
so difficult it blows them over. The key is to give

29:48.711 --> 29:54.078
them an assignment that pushes them to their next 
level of understanding. And then they get into the

29:54.098 --> 29:59.365
next level above that by succeeding at that 
previous level. But that takes differentiation

30:00.256 --> 30:02.939
and individualization. And that takes schools 
where teachers have their time. You can't do that

30:07.224 --> 30:11.749
with 200 kids in English. Each student in English 
is at a different stage in their ability to write.

30:15.793 --> 30:19.057
And you have to be working with them at the stage 
they're at. Some kids can do college work while

30:19.237 --> 30:22.420
they're in the sixth grade. And they ought to be 
allowed to proceed as far as they can. Other kids

30:26.845 --> 30:28.407
may have mild handicaps where they read from right 
to left rather than left to right. They can't make

30:32.481 --> 30:34.884
sense out of letters. They have dyslexia or 
something, some other problem. So the teacher

30:38.668 --> 30:42.833
needs to use different approaches with those 
kids. But a good school helps each student move as

30:43.033 --> 30:53.785
far as they can in terms of what they're able to do 
and still get them to feel good about themselves,

30:43.033 --> 30:53.785
not feel like a failure for life. And that's what 
I'm worried about with these strict models where

30:59.588 --> 31:05.837
everybody has to fit into the mold, and if they 
don't, they don't make it. They're kicked out. And

31:07.620 --> 31:22.002
five years from now, we may end up with the test 
averages going up, but when we take a look at it, we

31:07.620 --> 31:22.002
may find that the 20% of the kids who needed our help 
most are no longer in school. There'll be more

31:22.022 --> 31:27.570
people passing the test, but the other kids will 
have dropped out. And if that happens, we

31:28.698 --> 31:31.080
shouldn't call it reform. And I don't think that's 
what the governor or the select committee or any

31:31.161 --> 31:38.789
other people had in mind. They did this with the 
best intentions. But it could happen if we don't

31:41.511 --> 31:47.538
take a close look at it. In regard to the appraisal 
teams, do you think the one evaluator who must be

31:47.558 --> 31:57.388
from where the teacher is employed should be an 
administrator? and why? No, I think they should

31:59.143 --> 32:06.353
separate the administrator from the process of 
doing the evaluation. I think they should do like

32:06.373 --> 32:17.709
they're doing in Tennessee, bringing in people 
from the outside, the outside evaluators, who are

32:06.373 --> 32:17.709
specialists in the teaching field and as the 
teachers teach. This principal goes in there and

32:17.729 --> 32:27.662
he's not trained in physics to do an evaluation of 
the physics teacher or chemistry or science or

32:28.537 --> 32:31.061
foreign language. You need people who are trained 
in the subject areas and also trained to use the

32:31.081 --> 32:39.353
performance appraisal instruments. And then you 
also want a situation where you separate the

32:40.955 --> 32:56.738
evaluation from the person who's going to have to 
make that decision and help that person over the

32:40.955 --> 32:56.738
rough spots. You really need, in a school, people 
doing evaluations for merit and salary increases

32:58.220 --> 33:09.097
and promotions separate from evaluation from 
instruction improvement. The people who are

33:09.117 --> 33:25.543
working with people on instruction improvement, 
if the principal's going to be an instruction

33:09.117 --> 33:25.543
leader, the teacher has to be able to go to that 
principal without any fear at all or threat and

33:09.117 --> 33:25.543
tell all the bad things about themselves, things 
they don't know what to do. As a beginning teacher,

33:26.384 --> 33:31.211
for instance, you want to go in and say to the 
principal, boy, I'm having trouble with this.

33:31.232 --> 33:38.302
It's very hard to say that if that same person is 
going to turn around and have to evaluate you for

33:31.232 --> 33:38.302
merit. So you need these two systems of evaluation 
operating, one for instructional improvement

33:38.763 --> 33:53.466
and another for making judgments relating to 
personnel practices, such as salary increases

33:38.763 --> 33:53.466
and promotions. And those have to be separated.

33:57.586 --> 33:59.328
Are you for or against? The same person can't do 
both. It's a conflict of roles.

34:05.476 --> 34:10.062
Are you for or against the appointed or elected 
state board of education? I would like to see an

34:10.082 --> 34:19.694
elected state board with much more involvement of 
the local community in that process.

34:20.775 --> 34:26.142
But I worry about putting all this power and a few 
people who are appointed, and the political

34:27.472 --> 34:36.501
patronage that goes with these appointments to 
these boards. Now, first time around, everybody

34:36.521 --> 34:47.511
agreed that this particular governor would bend 
over backwards to make sure there was no political

34:36.521 --> 34:47.511
basis for doing the appointment. But there was an 
appointed board in Texas at one time, and they did

34:47.711 --> 34:56.820
away with it during the Elmore Aiken study. And the 
reason they went away with it because it became a

34:57.509 --> 35:13.428
political patronage appointment process where, 
over time, the politicians used these

34:57.509 --> 35:13.428
appointments as a political activity. And I 
believe that the more you take these kinds of roles

35:13.448 --> 35:22.960
out of the local community, the less investment 
and sense of ownership the local area has in the

35:23.547 --> 35:30.917
whole business of education. And I think that 
electing their officials to make these decisions

35:30.937 --> 35:41.752
is one of many of the things we ought to put back with 
the local board. I believe we ought to have a

35:41.772 --> 35:53.267
bottom-up approach for educational change with 
the individual school as the focus for

35:41.772 --> 35:53.267
improvement, not a top-down approach where you 
get a few people who are chosen because someone

35:54.125 --> 36:06.936
says we can't have any faith in these local boards, 
they're all controlled by the booster squad, and

35:54.125 --> 36:06.936
they'll be putting too much emphasis on 
athletics. Well, the key to that is to emphasize

36:06.956 --> 36:18.586
that the local board has to take the 
responsibility for quality, not to say let's take

36:06.956 --> 36:18.586
over that role. Because ultimately, a school is 
only as good as that local community wants to make

36:23.251 --> 36:25.715
it. You can't mandate quality for 1,089 school 
districts, 240,000 teachers, and 3.2 million

36:25.855 --> 36:43.442
children from the state and treat every school 
district as if they were one district. And because

36:43.702 --> 36:51.334
the districts vary from one end of the state to the 
other in terms of size, in terms of makeup, You've

36:52.006 --> 36:53.587
got the urban areas. You've got the small West 
Texas towns. But the key that you want is a

36:57.291 --> 37:08.061
commitment, regardless of the size of that 
district, of the local people in their schools to

36:57.291 --> 37:08.061
take the responsibility to make it good. Not a few 
people in

