41:40.827 --> 41:47.857
and we need to do a lot more about that. Teachers 
have to have a lot more autonomy in terms of the

41:47.877 --> 41:51.823
governance structure. We have to rely on teachers 
themselves to set the standards and monitor them.

41:56.369 --> 42:03.859
Actually, this bill took away from the Commission 
on Professional Standards much of its authority

41:56.369 --> 42:03.859
because the school state board itself now can give 
approval for local districts to set up

42:04.362 --> 42:13.151
alternative certification programs and bypass 
the commission of professional standards

42:04.362 --> 42:13.151
completely. So that was a step backward for the 
profession. The conditions in the workplace may

42:18.837 --> 42:25.263
be more important in many respects than the 
salary. If these essential elements

42:25.283 --> 42:32.310
requirements, which are requiring much more 
paperwork, The more the paper shuffling gets

42:33.303 --> 42:42.817
foisted on the teachers, we're going to drive a lot 
of them out of teaching. If you hand a teacher a

42:42.837 --> 43:02.365
syllabus and say, make sure everybody in this 
class is on page such and such on October 13th, and

42:42.837 --> 43:02.365
we're going to judge how good you are by giving them 
all a test, it changes the whole nature of teaching

42:42.837 --> 43:02.365
from a very creative process in which that teacher 
who loves their subject teaches it in the most

42:42.837 --> 43:02.365
creative ways possible. and then gets the 
students turned on instead of trying to do this

43:03.172 --> 43:10.460
workbook thing with these essential elements and 
then fill out the form. And a lot's going to happen

43:11.601 --> 43:31.002
in terms of the way the state loosens up and gets 
back to providing some of these teachers to trust

43:11.601 --> 43:31.002
them and have faith in them and give them some 
autonomy to teach these basic skills programs and

43:11.601 --> 43:31.002
beyond in creative ways. They'll take good 
leadership. I would like to see the state move

43:35.350 --> 43:53.577
toward a system where the better a school became, 
the more autonomy it would have, and reward them

43:35.350 --> 43:53.577
for being good by letting them develop innovative 
ways to do things, and not treat every school as if

43:35.350 --> 43:53.577
it was the same. Those schools which aren't doing a 
good job should be declared bankrupt, and the

43:53.597 --> 44:01.528
state should go in and do everything they can We're 
those, but not to put all of these minimum

44:01.762 --> 44:09.133
regulations on all of these really good school 
districts. Those good school districts ought to

44:09.153 --> 44:12.738
be rewarded by saying, do better. Think of 
creative things on your own that you can do to go

44:12.858 --> 44:22.292
beyond where you are, and the state then ought to 
provide incentives to help you do that.

44:22.312 --> 44:25.317
That's what will keep good teachers in teaching. 
If they have a chance to be creative and innovative

44:25.337 --> 44:29.423
and then get rewarded But the hard work it's going 
to take to go beyond the minimums.

