OK. What are the bad parts of Haskell 72? Well, I 
think the overemphasis on testing as an indicator

44:40.787 --> 44:47.013
of excellence. There are many more ways to define 
excellence than just test scores. You know, I

44:53.859 --> 44:57.823
think that the...

44:59.035 --> 45:13.411
aspects of the bill with the over-emphasis on 
threat as the primary means for motivation, the

44:59.035 --> 45:13.411
whole business of the no more than five days 
absent. Here, kids, you see, those kinds of

45:13.431 --> 45:25.524
things, the regulations, when you try to 
implement those, having been a principal of a

45:13.431 --> 45:25.524
school and a teacher, I know that you need the 
flexibility in a school. The assumption is if you

45:26.165 --> 45:28.367
don't have those rules, kids will you know, not, 
they'll abuse them. Well, there are other ways to

45:35.025 --> 45:39.352
get kids to go to school other than having those 
rules. You may have a situation, for instance,

45:39.372 --> 45:49.587
where you have a migrant farm worker student who, 
in order to keep the family going, has to work

45:39.372 --> 45:49.587
during certain times of the year. We used to be the 
kids where any day you could get that child in

45:50.088 --> 45:55.536
school, you were happy to get them there. You 
wanted to get them there. And now that kid misses

45:57.592 --> 46:15.697
five days of school, and he might as well stay out of 
school for the whole semester, because even if he

45:57.592 --> 46:15.697
comes back, which he's not going to when you sit 
there and not get any credit for it, he misses the

45:57.592 --> 46:15.697
five days, he loses the whole semester, which is 
absurd. What you want to do is set up a system where

46:15.777 --> 46:22.366
you get him in school as many days as you possibly 
can working. That's going to be a system where

46:22.386 --> 46:26.552
after five days, after they miss five days, 
they'll give up. It's just like having this six

46:27.089 --> 46:35.437
weeks as a suspension time for people who don't get 
